    <section class="section">
      <h2>How We Work</h2>
      <p>
        ReServe connects <strong>food donors</strong> and <strong>NGOs (receivers)</strong> through a smooth,
        tech-backed process that ensures no edible food goes to waste. Our mission is simple —
        we bridge the gap between surplus and need, turning excess into hope.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Who Are the Donors?</h2>
      <p>
        Donors are places where surplus food is commonly generated — whether due to over-preparation or unserved
        portions.
        Instead of wasting this perfectly good food, they share it through ReServe to support communities in need.
      </p>
      <ul class="donor-list">
        <li>Restaurants and Cafes with leftover unsold meals</li>
        <li>Buffet Halls, Banquets, and Wedding Caterers with untouched food</li>
        <li>Corporate Canteens and College Messes after meal hours</li>
        <li>Event Organizers and Hotels hosting large gatherings</li>
        <li>Food Production Units with daily surplus batches</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Who Are the Receivers?</h2>
      <p>
        Receivers are verified NGOs and social organizations who collect the donated food safely and quickly.
        They ensure every meal reaches people who truly need it — from homeless communities to orphanages and shelters.
      </p>
      <ul class="receiver-list">
        <li>Non-Governmental Organizations (NGOs)</li>
        <li>Community Shelters and Old Age Homes</li>
        <li>Children’s Orphanages</li>
        <li>Food Banks and Local Welfare Groups</li>
        <li>Volunteer-Led Distribution Networks</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Our Process</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>1. Listing:</strong> Donors list their surplus food on the ReServe platform, specifying quantity,
        cuisine type, and pickup time.<br><br>
        <strong>2. Notification:</strong> Nearby NGOs receive instant alerts about available food through our
        system.<br><br>
        <strong>3. Collection:</strong> NGO volunteers arrive at the donor’s location, following hygiene and safety
        protocols.<br><br>
        <strong>4. Verification:</strong> Food is quality-checked to ensure it’s fresh, safe, and fit for
        consumption.<br><br>
        <strong>5. Distribution:</strong> The food is transported directly to community kitchens, shelters, or local
        welfare points.<br><br>
        <strong>6. Impact Tracking:</strong> Both donor and receiver can track how their contribution made a difference
        — every plate counts.
      </p>
    </section>
